- "Publications" are the scholarly works produced by researchers;
- "Citations" are the number of times a publication is referenced by other works;
- "Authors" are the individuals who contribute to a publication.

- "Prolific researchers" refers to those with the highest number of publications;
- "Top collaborations" refers to the most frequent collaborations between researchers;
- "Top-cited publications" refers to the publications with the highest number of citations;
- "High publication count" indicates a significant number of publications;
- "Significant average altmetric score" suggests that the publications have received considerable attention beyond citations.

- "blossomed with more than 5 research papers" refers to researchers who have published more than 5 papers;
- "stand tall among their peers with highly cited works" refers to researchers whose publications have a citation count greater than the average citation count;
- "woven a web of collaborations involving at least 3 other researchers" refers to researchers who have collaborated on more than 2 publications.

sql:
SELECT T1.title
FROM publications AS T1
JOIN citation_counts AS T2 ON T1.pub_id = T2.pub_id
WHERE T2.citation_count = (
  SELECT MAX(citation_count) FROM citation_counts
);

